{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655786"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:05:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:05:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18680"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18680"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.22,0.57,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11412"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79554"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11412"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64858"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7126"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26442"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79554"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe caudate nucleus is an important structure within the basal ganglia of the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the caudate nucleus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Control of autonomic functions","Integration of sensory information","Motor control and learning","Production of cerebrospinal fluid","Regulation of sleep cycles"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emotor control and learning\u003C/strong\u003E functions are the primary roles of the caudate nucleus. As part of the basal ganglia, it receives input from the cerebral cortex and forms part of circuits involved in movement initiation, motor learning, and procedural memory.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of cerebrospinal fluid\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of the choroid plexus within the ventricles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntegration of sensory information\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily performed by the thalamus and sensory cortices\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulation of sleep cycles\u003C/strong\u003E - This is mainly controlled by the hypothalamus and brainstem structures\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControl of autonomic functions\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily managed by the hypothalamus and brainstem nuclei\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe caudate nucleus works in conjunction with other basal ganglia structures to modulate motor output through both direct and indirect pathways. It receives dopaminergic input from the substantia nigra and projects to the globus pallidus as part of these motor control circuits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The caudate nucleus is a key component of the basal ganglia involved in motor control and learning.","The caudate nucleus receives input primarily from the cerebral cortex and projects to the globus pallidus.","The caudate nucleus forms part of the dorsal striatum along with the putamen."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevi